{
  "answer": "In Cynewulf's *Elene* (the sole chapter), Helena (Elene) arrives in Jerusalem and summons assemblies of learned Jews (first 3,000, then 1,000, then 500) to interrogate them about their scriptures' prophecies of Christ and, ultimately, the location where \"the Lord had suffered\" (i.e., Calvary, site of the True Cross).[^1] She quotes Moses, David, Isaiah et al. accusing them of rejecting the prophesied Messiah, presses them repeatedly (\"the queen began to press them with words\"), and threatens mass execution by fire when they stonewall her, at which point they hand over Judas (who knows the secret).[^2]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-7b1c1f).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).",
